{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti**, **Pārāśara Smṛti**, **Yājñavalkya Smṛti**, **Āṅgirasa Smṛti**, and **Bṛhaspati Smṛti** discuss rules for hospitality to guests (*atithi*), primarily as part of the householder's daily duties (*mahāyajñas*) alongside offerings to gods, ancestors, and beings. These texts, rooted in dharmaśāstra traditions, emphasize honoring guests arriving unexpectedly (especially at sunset during the Vaiśvadeva rite), providing a seat, water, food, and protection, regardless of status (even sinners or outcastes if during Vaiśvadeva). Neglect leads to ancestral dissatisfaction and hellish rebirths. Detailed procedures include ritual precedence, exclusions (e.g., non-atithis from the same village), and expiations.[^1][^2][^3][^4][^5]\n\nNo other works in the corpus cover prescriptive rules; scattered mentions (e.g., poetry like *Andreas* or *Bang-e-Dara*) describe hospitality culturally but lack normative guidelines.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 3, [translation](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-0c3bc7).\n\n[^2]: Pārāśara Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation](/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-40daa2).\n\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-76e5e9).\n\n[^4]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-b4c044).\n\n[^5]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-a9c1cd).",
